<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangxi To Practice Revenue-Sharing System </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1802113694 Nanning Guangxi People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 1130 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1802113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Nanning Guangxi People's Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Guangxi Regional People's Government recently 
promulgated a decision on the implementation of a 
revenue-sharing system. The decision points out: The 
implementation of a revenue-sharing system is a major decision 
of the party Central Committee and the State Council and is an 
important element of economic structural reform. 
  The decision demands: Following the implementation a 
revenue- sharing system, first, it is necessary to strengthen 
graded budgetary management, and an additional expenditure 
should be borne by the relevant administrative level. The 
regional government will not bear expenditures which should be 
borne by a prefecture, city, or county, or vice versa. Second, 
it is necessary to strengthen management over administrative 
spending, to improve control over administrative expenditures, 
to exercise strict management over expenditure limits, and to 
encourage departments with the necessary conditions to increase 
their income. 
  Third, it is necessary to strengthen management over the 
collections of administrative charges and to put them under 
budgetary management so as to prevent the loss of revenue. 
Fourth, it is necessary to strengthen management over 
extrabudgetary funds. The administrative departments' budgetary 
and extrabudgetary revenue should be put in a uniform revenue 
and expenditure plan. Fifth, it is necessary to forge a balance 
between revenue and expenditures. Under the revenue-sharing 
system, prefectures and cities should work out their budgets in 
such a way that a balance between revenue and expenditures can 
be maintained with some surpluses. The regional financial 
department is not responsible for making up prefectures' or 
cities' deficits; in such cases, the prefectures and cities 
should make efforts to resolve them. 
  The decision stresses: The implementation of the 
revenue-sharing system is a major step in financial reform. All 
prefectural administrative offices and city governments should 
strengthen their leadership to ensure its smooth implementation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

