<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Rejects Tariff Cuts in Upcoming U.S. Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2002124094 Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network in Mandarin 2300 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2002124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] The Agricultural Council under the Executive Yuan 
stated yesterday that it could not agree to lower all tariffs 
for individual agricultural products to below 20 percent and 
that Taiwan will not categorically refuse the [word indistinct] 
proposed by the United States, noting the need to wait until the 
major supplying countries and the final results of the 
negotiations [as heard]. The bilateral consultation meeting with 
the United States over Taiwan's joining the GATT will begin next 
Thursday [24 February]. 
  The Agricultural Council is said to be working out the 
bottom 
line in talks and the room for maneuver in lowering the tariffs 
in view of the United States' call for the lowering of tariffs 
on 387 items. It is said that the percentage for tariff 
reductions on 387 items is greater than that requested by the 
United States during the talks on tariff cuts in January, and 
that the United States wants Taiwan to slash tariffs on the 
majority of agricultural products by more than 50 percent. The 
United States also requested Taiwan not to set all tariffs on 
individual agricultural products at higher than 20 percent. 
  At the upcoming bilateral consultation meeting with the 
United States over Taiwan's joining GATT, the United States is 
expected to again call on Taiwan to further slash tariffs on the 
over 100 agricultural products on which Taiwan had earlier 
agreed in the talks in January to make cuts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

