<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Lift Restrictions on Apple Imports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102083694 Taipei CNA in English 0708 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Feb. 21 (CNA) -- Taiwan will lift its import 
restrictions on apples in preparation for entry into the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the Council of Agriculture (COA) 
said Sunday [20 February]. 
  However, imported apples will face even stricter quarantine 
measures after the restrictions are lifted, especially those 
from the United States, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa and 
Chile, which have been declared codling moth regions, the COA 
added. 
  COA officials said that Taiwan currently limits the purchase 
of apples from the US and allows limited imports from Japan, 
Australia and New Zealand. 
  The officials said that after lifting the restrictions, 
apples from Japan and Korea will have the competitive edge here 
while apples from the US, Australia and New Zealand will not be 
allowed in if they do not meet the stricter quarantine measures. 
  COA officials said that the enhanced quarantine measures are 
necessary to protect domestic agriculture in the face of an 
expected flood of imported apples. 
  Australia and New Zealand have expressed concern about the 
new quarantine measures, Sun Ming-hsien, COA chairman, said upon 
his return home Sunday from a weeklong visit to New Zealand. 
  Sun said he has agreed to a New Zealand request for a 
meeting 
on the measures. The time of the meeting has yet to be set, he 
noted. 
  Australia is also expected to raise the issue of the new 
quarantine measures during a scheduled meeting with COA in March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

