<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Counterfeit Charge on Video Products `Baseless' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102063094 Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network in Mandarin 2300 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2102063094 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei China Broadcasting Corporation News 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday, Nintendo Corporation of America and some 
60 video game cartridge companies formally called on U.S. Trade 
Representative Office to keep Taiwan included on the special 301 
priority watchlist. 
  (Vansaw), legal adviser to Nintendo, pointed out that as 
Taiwan is still allowing the export of fake Nintendo video game 
products all over the world, Taiwan still remains the world's 
major source of fake products. 
  Yesterday, the Board of Foreign Trade under the Ministry of 
Economic Affairs lodged a strong protest over Nintendo 
Corporation of America's request of the U.S. Trade 
Representative Office to blacklist Taiwan on the special 301 
priority watchlist and over the release of a newsletter in which 
Nintendo accused Taiwan's manufacturers of heavy involvement in 
the production of counterfeit products. (Cai Nian-sen), head of 
the Third Division of the Board of Foreign Trade, pointed out 
that as Nintendo Corporation of America's charge against Taiwan 
is baseless and as Nintendo showed no sincerity in cooperating 
with Taiwan's practicing an export inspection system involving 
Taiwan's computer products, it has to bear the responsibility 
for the serious counterfeiting of its products. 

</TEXT>

