<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pretoria May Switch Diplomatic Ties to PRC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2202061294 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
20 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2202061294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News" program] </F>
  [Text] Even if the African National Congress [ANC] wins in 
the 27 April general election in South Africa, it cannot simply 
dictate Pretoria's foreign policy. The ANC, which is expected 
to win the first multiracial election in South Africa, has close 
ties with Mainland China. There have been indications that once 
the ANC heads the government, South Africa will switch its 
diplomatic recognition from Taipei to Peking. 
  According to visiting South African Justice Deputy Minister 
Shelia Camerer, the National Party would like to maintain close 
trade links with Taiwan. Since the government will be a 
government of national unity -- a coalition government -- 
Camerer said, the National Party, headed by the president after 
De Klerk, will still be a part of the government. She said the 
National Party will work hard to maintain South Africa's ties 
with the ROC [Republic of China], a position which the party 
will not give up easily. 
  South Africa is the only major country that has maintained 
diplomatic ties with the ROC. 

</TEXT>

