<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai's Major Exchanges Use High-Tech Equipment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2102033494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0316 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2102033494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, February 21 (XINHUA) -- Computerized 
business using satellite communications have been carried out 
successfully in Shanghai's ten major exchanges. 
  Open since 1990, these exchanges are involved in the fields 
of securities, metals, chemicals, grain and edible oil, motor 
vehicles, petroleum, building materials, technology, coal and 
farm capital. 
  By updating its central computer system several times, the 
Shanghai stock market is able to handle 1,800 transactions per 
second at present, up from only six in the past. 
  Officials with the Shanghai stock exchange said that nearly 
eight million U.S. dollars were spent to upgrade the whole 
system, which uses optical fibre communication lines to link up 
exchanges of other regions. 
  At present, the trading of Shanghai's stocks can be carried 
out in other major cities via satellite communication channels. 
A nationwide securities market is in shape. 
  High technology has made brisk business possible. 
  In only three years, the daily transaction volume of the 
Shanghai stock market has jumped from the original 105,000 yuan 
to an average of 900 million yuan. Now more than five million 
people are holding Shanghai stocks and trading at 500 markets in 
different regions. 
  With the help of the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges, 
all leading cities in the mainland, including Lhasa, capital of 
the Tibet Autonomous Region, have opened stock market. 
  At present, the Shanghai grain and oil and metal exchanges 
are also releasing and receiving market information via 
satellite communications. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

